      "title": "Ticket vs Physical Product: Five Key Differences",
      "content": "When you compare a ticket to a tangible good, five stark differences emerge:\n\n| Aspect | Ticket (Intangible) | Physical Product |\n|--------|---------------------|------------------|\n| **Ownership** | Grants a **right** to attend, not an item you keep. | Grants **possession** of a material object.\n| **Tangibility** | No physical form; delivered digitally or printed. | Concrete, can be touched, stored, displayed.\n| **Inventory Management** | Unlimited digital copies; capacity limited by venue seats. | Finite stock; each unit occupies warehouse space.\n| **Consumption Timing** | **Immediate** – value realized at the event moment; often non‑refundable. | Can be used **later**; may be returned or exchanged.\n| **Return/Refund Policy** | Usually **non‑refundable** once the event is confirmed; resale markets may exist. | Often **refundable** or exchangeable within a set period.\n\nThese differences shape how you sell, price, and support your customers. For example, because tickets are non‑refundable, you must focus on **pre‑sale assurance** – clear event details, safety measures, and strong brand trust. In contrast, physical products allow post‑sale service like warranties or returns, shifting the sales emphasis to after‑sales support. Understanding these gaps equips you to tailor your sales scripts, marketing collateral, and customer service approaches specifically for the ticket market.",
